  <h2>Liver Support</h2>
  <section>

  <p>
    The liver is your body’s primary detox organ, central to immune signaling and antigen clearance.
    It processes toxins, hormones, and inflammatory byproducts — and when it’s healthy, your whole
    body benefits. Taking steps to support your liver rewards you with fewer immune triggers,
    balanced hormones, and a stronger, healthier body.
  </p>

  <p><strong>Here’s how your liver works for you every day:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Filters toxins</strong> and cleans your blood</li>
    <li><strong>Balances hormones</strong> by processing excess amounts</li>
    <li><strong>Activates key nutrients</strong> like vitamins A, D, E, and K</li>
    <li><strong>Supports digestion</strong> by producing bile for fat breakdown</li>
    <li><strong>Helps your immune system</strong> by clearing harmful byproducts and antigens</li>
  </ul>
</section>


  <h3>Key Liver-Supporting Nutrients with Strong Evidence</h3>
  <ul class="bullets">
    <li><strong>Curcumin</strong> (from turmeric) antioxidant and anti-inflammatory actions; researched in NAFLD/NASH contexts <sup>11</sup>. <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28158893/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Study</a></li>
    <li><strong>Green Tea Catechins</strong> EGCG and related catechins studied for liver fat and inflammation modulation <sup>9</sup>. <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24065295/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Study</a></li>
    <li><strong>Green Tea </strong> EGCG reduced body weight and improved insulin resistance in mice<sup>9</sup>. <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/aps201511?" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Study</a></li>
    <li><strong>Dandelion Root</strong> traditional choleretic; emerging data on hepatoprotective effects <sup>10</sup>. <a href="https://journals.lww.com/aptb/fulltext/2020/10010/hepatoprotection_by_dandelion__taraxacum.1.aspx?" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Study</a></li>
    <li><strong>Milk Thistle</strong> (silymarin) long-studied hepatoprotective complex with antioxidant activity <sup>8</sup>. <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3894463/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Study</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h4 style="font-size: 1rem; margin-top: 1rem;">Other Liver Supporting Research Worth Mentioning</h4>
  <ul class="bullets">
    <li><strong>Vitamin E</strong> RCTs in non-diabetic NASH; pediatric benefit in TONIC trial <sup>12</sup>. 
  <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20427778/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Study</a>. 
  That means in this group, Vitamin E actually helped more people improve their liver disease compared to the placebo group. They took it by mouth orally. In the PIVENS trial, participants were given 800IU of vitamin E daily to take orally for 96 weeks. In the Tonic trial, participants received 400IU twice daily for 96 weeks.
</li>

    <li><strong>Coffee</strong>  meta-analyses associate intake with lower fibrosis risk and improved outcomes in chronic liver disease <sup>13</sup>. <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8471033/?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/apt.13523" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"></a>Study</a></li>
    <li><strong>Omega-3 fatty acids</strong> (n-3 PUFAs)  trials show liver fat reduction and lipid improvements in NAFLD <sup>14</sup>. <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39347373/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Study</a></li>
    <li><strong>Artichoke Leaf Extract</strong> RCTs: reductions in ALT/AST and ultrasound markers of fatty liver & increased hepatic vein flow <sup>15</sup>. <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29520889/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Study</a></li>
    <li>
  <strong>N-acetylcysteine (NAC)</strong>:  
  - In a 3-month RCT (600 mg twice daily), NAC significantly lowered ALT and reduced spleen size in NAFLD patients.  
  - In hepatotoxic drug (e.g., tuberculosis regimen) trials, NAC prevented spikes in transaminases when added prophylactically.  
  - It also improved ALT, AST, ALP, and CHILD-Pugh/MELD scores in more advanced liver impairment.  
  - Animal studies show NAC reduces oxidative stress, steatosis, and restores glutathione in NAFLD models.  
  <sup>[refs]</sup>
</li>

  </ul>

